\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.5}{\ignorespaces Recorded zenith absorption spectrum in the $160-520$\nobreakspace {}GHz range, taken on Mauna Kea at an altitude of $\approx 4000$\nobreakspace {}m. The data has been fit to a sum of $\rm H_20$ lines, an $\rm H_20$ pseudo-continuum and dry absorption lines. The model has been generated using the \textsc {atm} code (see section\nobreakspace {}\ref {sec:atm_theory}), with the bottom panel showing the residuals. Here `dry' refers to all atmospheric constituents except $\rm H_20$. Reproduced from \citet {Pardo_2001} \relax }}{52}{figure.caption.21}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.6}{\ignorespaces A log-log plot of RMS visibility phase versus baseline length for an observation of 1\nobreakspace {}Jy source 0748\nobreakspace {}+\nobreakspace {}240 with VLA at 22\nobreakspace {}GHz over a 90\nobreakspace {}min duration. The open circles show RMS phase as measured whereas the solid squares show the same values with a constant thermal noise contribution of $10^\circ $ subtracted in quadrature. Note that the measured and theoretical Kolmogorov turbulent exponent $\beta $ changes with distance on the phase screen as the viewing configuration transitions from a thick screen ($\beta _{\rm theory} = 5/3$) to a thin screen ($\beta _{\rm theory} = 2/3$) at $r \approx 1$\nobreakspace {}km and from a thin screen to completely uncorrelated regime ($\beta = 0$) beyond the outer scale at $r \approx 6$\nobreakspace {}km. Although these regimes appear distinct, there is continous variation between them. Reproduced from \citet *{Carilli_1997} \relax }}{57}{figure.caption.24}
